<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">GLOBAL STOCK MARKETS SHAKEN <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The European markets have been exuberant for months, with investors eager to make bold bets on risky assets like Portuguese bonds, Spanish construction companies and Greek banks. But investors received a jolt on Thursday when shares of Portugalâs second-largest bank, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/10/what-to-do-about-banco-espirito-santo-of-portugal">Banco EspÃ­rito Santo</a></b>, were suspended from trading, prompting fears that the bank might need to be rescued, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/11/business/daily-stock-market-activity.html">Landon Thomas Jr. and Peter Eavis write in DealBook</a></b>. The move sent highflying stocks and bonds in Portugal plummeting, forced two Spanish companies to suspend bond offerings and brought concerns over the health of Europeâs banking system.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Mr. Thomas and Mr. Eavis write</b>: âAs markets from Germany to Greece wobbled, the tumult was a reminder to investors as to how quickly bad news can spread in the euro zone. At a time when the European Central Bank is scrutinizing banks, the problems at EspÃ­rito Santo are raising fears that there may be unpleasant surprises in banking systems in Greece, Spain and Italy.â Some regulators are <b>concerned that unorthodox bond buying by central banks</b> has created frothy markets, particularly in high-yielding debt in European and emerging markets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The economic problems were localized, but fears of more endemic issues were enough to <b>scare markets</b> on Thursday. The Euro Stoxx 50 index of European stocks was off more than 1.6 percent, and Portugalâs main stock index fell 4.2 percent. European stocks <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/reuters/2014/07/11/business/11reuters-markets-global.html?ref=international&#038;_r=0">opened stronger on Friday</a></b>, as markets settled. The Dow Jones industrial average and the Standard &#038; Poorâs 500-stock index were each down less than 1 percent on Thursday.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">THE TALK OF SUN VALLEY <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Allen &#038; Companyâs annual conference in Sun Valley, Idaho, isnât just about hushed merger talks between media and technology moguls, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/10/the-talk-of-sun-valley-its-not-just-about-deals">Michael J. de la Merced writes in DealBook</a></b>. This year, education reform, national service and creativity were also among the topics of discussion. Other upcoming panels look promising as well, according to attendees, including one on the Middle East, scheduled for Saturday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">During a discussion about education reform, <b>Gov. Chris Christie of New Jersey</b> declared to the assembled audience that if supporters of charter schools wanted to defeat the teachersâ unions, they would have to spend at least as much money on lobbying. And Gen. Stanley A. McChrystal, a former commander of the United Statesâ armed forces in Afghanistan, drew the attention of attendees during a discussion with Tom Brokaw on <b>universal national service</b>. Also popular with many attendees was a panel on creativity, moderated by Charlie Rose and featuring Hollywood bigwigs like Brian Grazer and Harvey Weinstein.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But good luck attending any of these discussions as a nonconference guest at the mountain resort. Security has always been tight during the conference, but this year, the cordon became <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/10/security-is-tight-at-sun-valley-conference">that much tighter</a></b>. Large portions of the resort are blocked off, and one of the pools is closed. During the evenings, the Duchin bar, just off the Sun Valley Lodgeâs lobby, is off limits for nonconference guests. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even for conference attendees, who have more access to the resort, <b>one guest has been hard to find</b>. Despite attracting considerable buzz, Marissa Mayer, the chief executive of Yahoo, has remained largely out of public view. <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/10/tracking-sun-valleys-most-wanted-guest-marissa-mayer">DealBook spotted Ms. Mayer</a></b> heading into a meeting in the Sun Valley Lodge with executives including Hiroshi Mikitani, the chief executive of the Japanese e-commerce company Rakuten, which owns a stake in the social network Pinterest and recently acquired Viber, a fast-growing Internet calling and messaging service. But a half-hour later, Ms. Mayer left.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">TRW GETS PRELIMINARY TAKEOVER BID <span class="divider"> | </span></span> TRW Automotive Holdings, one of the largest auto safety parts makers, has received a preliminary nonbinding offer to be acquired by ZF Friedrichshafen, a German auto parts maker, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/10/trw-automotive-gets-preliminary-takeover-offer">David Gelles writes in DealBook</a></b>. TRW, based in Livonia, Mich., did not identify the suitor, but the German company confirmed that it had had discussions on a possible acquisition. TRW, which has a market value of more than $10 billion, said in a statement that it had <b>not decided whether it would engage in sale talks</b> and had not set a timetable for making a decision. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The <b>Treasuryâs monthly budget report</b> for June is out at 2 p.m. <b>Wells Fargo</b> reports second-quarter earnings before the bell.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Charles I. Plosser</b>, president of the Philadelphia Fed, moderates a panel on entrepreneurial issues during the morning session at the Rocky Mountain Economic Summit in Jackson Hole, Wyo. During the afternoon session, <b>Charles L. Evans</b>, president of the Chicago Fed, and <b>Dennis P. Lockhart</b>, president of the Atlanta Fed, discuss Federal Reserve policy on a panel.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>World Cup watch</b>: <b>Brazil vs. Netherlands</b> in the third place match at 4 p.m. on Saturday. <b>Germany vs. Argentina</b> in the finals at 3 p.m. on Sunday.<br />
</p>
