<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">STEVEN COHEN WRITES A BIG CHECK <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Steven A. Cohenâs former hedge fund, SAC Capital Advisors, paid a $900 million penalty to prosecutors on Tuesday, 90 days after the firmâs guilty plea to insider trading charges was approved by a federal judge, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/10/steven-cohen-writes-a-big-check-to-the-u-s-government">Matthew Goldstein writes in DealBook</a></b>. The 90-day window to pay the penalty, part of an overall $1.2 billion criminal settlement reached with prosecutors last November, was three times the 30-day recommendation by the courtâs probation department. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The extra two months to pay the criminal penalty gave Mr. Cohenâs newly christened family office, Point72 Asset Management, <b>more flexibility to deploy capital</b> to the roughly 80 portfolio managers and trading teams that remain with his firm. Point72, with more than 800 employees, now trades as much as $10 billion of Mr. Cohenâs personal wealth.</p>
